### Summary

The use of `Canvas.FillPolygonOutline(Vector2[], float, float, float, float)` with a negative second parameter (width) will cause an incorrect outline which is not pixel correct to the specified negative width.

### How to reproduce [Bugs]

* Create a new Duality project
* Create a new component with the following code:
```
public class OutlineTest : Component, ICmpRenderer
{
  public float BoundRadius { get; }

  public void Draw(IDrawDevice device)
  {
    const float borderWidth = 5;
    const float minPos = 100;
    const float maxPos = 200;
    var canvas = new Canvas(device);

    canvas.PushState();
    canvas.State.ColorTint = ColorRgba.Red;

    // Polygon outer border
    canvas.DrawPolygon(new[] { new Vector2(minPos - borderWidth, minPos - borderWidth), new Vector2(maxPos + borderWidth, minPos - borderWidth), new Vector2(maxPos + borderWidth, maxPos + borderWidth), new Vector2(minPos - borderWidth, maxPos + borderWidth) }, 0, 0, 1);

    // Polygon position
    canvas.DrawPolygon(new[] { new Vector2(minPos, minPos), new Vector2(maxPos, minPos), new Vector2(maxPos, maxPos), new Vector2(minPos, maxPos) }, 0, 0, 1);

    // Polygon inner border
    canvas.DrawPolygon(new[] { new Vector2(minPos + borderWidth, minPos + borderWidth), new Vector2(maxPos - borderWidth, minPos + borderWidth), new Vector2(maxPos - borderWidth, maxPos - borderWidth), new Vector2(minPos + borderWidth, maxPos - borderWidth) }, 0, 0, 1);

    canvas.PopState();

    // Fill outer outline
    canvas.PushState();
    canvas.State.ColorTint = ColorRgba.White;
    canvas.FillPolygonOutline(new[] { new Vector2(minPos, minPos), new Vector2(maxPos, minPos), new Vector2(maxPos, maxPos), new Vector2(minPos, maxPos) }, borderWidth, 0, 0, 10);
    canvas.PopState();

    // Fill inner outline (wrong results here)
    canvas.PushState();
    canvas.State.ColorTint = ColorRgba.Blue;
    canvas.FillPolygonOutline(new[] { new Vector2(minPos, minPos), new Vector2(maxPos, minPos), new Vector2(maxPos, maxPos), new Vector2(minPos, maxPos) }, -borderWidth, 0, 0, 10);
    canvas.PopState();
  }

  public bool IsVisible(IDrawDevice device)
  {
    if ((device.VisibilityMask & VisibilityFlag.ScreenOverlay) != VisibilityFlag.None) return false;
    if ((device.VisibilityMask & device.VisibilityMask & VisibilityFlag.AllGroups) == VisibilityFlag.None) return false;
    return true;
  }
}
```
* Place the component on the scene
* Set the perspective of the main camera to flat and place the camera right above the now drawn rectangles

The component draws three polygons in red representing the intended polygon itself in its middle and the two borders, one outer border and one inner border. Both borders have the same distance to the intended polygon.

The white drawn outline is correct, because it touches the red outer polygon line and begins at the intended polying. In contrast the blue drawn outline begins at the intended polygon, but exceeds the red inner polygon by far. My expectation is, that even when using negative width at `Canvas.FillPolygonOutline` it draws a inner outline with correct pixel width.

### Workaround [Bugs]

No clean workaround is known. You can only try to adjust the negative width with a number which will result in the desired inner outline. For the sample used dividing the negative width with 7.065f will produce an acceptable result. But this does not seem to work for other shapes.

### Attachments

![innerpolygonoutlinebug](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/30325942/29752769-6156ba82-8b64-11e7-906e-9457f03ff3e4.jpg)

### Summary

Add a better way to render to texture.

### Analysis [Feature Requests]

Currenly Duality uses RenderTargets to render to texture. This is fine when you use them in the editor, but becomes real problem when you need to do it dynamicly at runtime.

To render one frame with a shader to a texture you need to do this. At least I haven't found another way. (Code untested)

`            RenderTarget target = new RenderTarget();
            Texture tex = new Texture();
            tex.Size = new Vector2(100, 100);

            ContentProvider.AddContent(@"Data\Temp\tex.Texture.res", tex);
            target.Targets = new ContentRef<Texture>[] { ContentProvider.RequestContent<Texture>(@"Data\Temp\tex.Texture.res") };

            RenderTarget target2 = new RenderTarget();
            Texture tex2 = new Texture();
            tex2.Size = new Vector2(100, 100);

            ContentProvider.AddContent(@"Data\Temp\tex2.Texture.res", tex2);
            target2.Targets = new ContentRef<Texture>[] { ContentProvider.RequestContent<Texture>(@"Data\Temp\tex2.Texture.res") };

            BatchInfo batch = new BatchInfo();
            batch.Technique = ContentProvider.RequestContent<DrawTechnique>(@"Data/ExampleTechnique");
            //this wont work, because batch.Textures is a IEnumerable<KeyValuePair<string, Texture>>()
            batch.Textures = tex2;

            ContentProvider.AddContent(@"Data\Temp\target2.RenderTarget.res", target2);
            
            DrawDevice dev = new DrawDevice();
            dev.Target = ContentProvider.RequestContent<RenderTarget>(@"Data\Temp\target2.RenderTarget.res");

            Canvas canv = new Canvas(dev);
            canv.State.SetMaterial(batch);
            canv.FillRect(0, 0, 100, 100);`

Possible Solutions:
- Allow Renderer to change the target
- Add GameObject equivalents for Resources needed for shaders/RenderToTexture
- Add a simple new API for drawing to a FrameBuffer
- Maybe add a "Resource Prefab"?

### Attachments

- [Bugs] Complete Logfiles (if available)
- [Bugs] Screenshots (if applicable and useful)
- [Feature Requests] Mockup screenshots and sketches (if applicable and useful)

### Summary
The following suggestions were gathered while using the engine for a number of projects. The intention is to make one's life easier by providing shortcuts for common calculations.

### List of suggestions

1. Vector component properties for `Vector2` and `Vector3` types. Obtaining the X, Y and Z vector components quickly. Names are arguable.
Implementation example:
``` csharp
struct Vector3 {
    Vector3 XVector { get { return new Vector3 (this.X, 0f, 0f); } }
    Vector3 YVector { get { return new Vector3 (0f, this.Y, 0f); } }
    Vector3 ZVector { get { return new Vector3 (0f, 0f, this.Z); } }
}
```

2. More coordinate selector properties for `Rect`. Convenient access for: `TopMiddle`, `RightMiddle`, `BottomMiddle` and `LeftMiddle` coordinates.

3. A saturation function to the `MathF` class. Similar to `Sign`, but accepts an epsilon value too.
Implementation example:
``` csharp
float Saturate (float val, float eps)
{
    if (Abs (val) <= eps) return 0f;
    return Sign (val);
}
```
4. `Clamp` is quite often used with `0f` and `1f` as boundaries. Let's create a function for that: `Clamp01`.

5. Inverse linear interpolation to `MathF`, and possibly to `Vector2` and `Vector3`.
Implementation example:
``` csharp
float InvLerp (float value, float min, float max)
{
    return (value - min) / (max - min);
}
```

6. Inverse linear interpolation with `0f` and `1f` as boundaries.

7. Introduce the well known `smoothstep` function to `MathF`. The formula is `x * x * (3 - 2 * x)`.

When u are using the following class, the editor set for T "Single" by default. 
```CSharp
public class MyClass<T>
{
	public T Foo { get; set; }

	public T Bar { get; set; }
}
```
![](https://thumbs.gfycat.com/ImpartialOpulentGoldenretriever-size_restricted.gif)

So I can't use "string" or "boolean" as T.

It would be nice if the editor would bring up a dialogue where you can choose the type of T.
Like this:
![](http://i.imgur.com/mEXQ7ch.png)
